 problems.</span></li><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"> <span class=\"cf\" htag=\"span\" hclass=\"cf\">permit somebody/something to do something</span> <span class=\"x\">Cash machines permit you to withdraw money at any time.</span></li></ul><div class=\"collapse\" hclass=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\"><span class=\"unbox\" unbox=\"snippet\" id=\"permit2_unbox_5\"><span class=\"box_title\">Oxford Collocations Dictionary</span><span class=\"body\"><span class=\"unbox\">adverb</span><ul class=\"collocs_list\"><li class=\"li\">legally</li><li class=\"li\">generally</li><li class=\"li\">normally</li><li class=\"li\">…</li></ul><span class=\"unbox\">verb + permit</span><ul class=\"collocs_list\"><li class=\"li\">refuse to</li><li class=\"li\">be designed to</li></ul><span class=\"xref_to_full_entry\">See <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/collocations/permit_2\" title=\" definition in Collocations\n \">full entry</a></span></span></span></div>      </li><div class=\"collapse\" hclass=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\"><span class=\"unbox\" id=\"permit2_unbox_6\" unbox=\"wordorigin\"><span class=\"box_title\">Word Origin</span><span class=\"body\"><span class=\"p\">late Middle English (originally in the sense ‘commit, hand over’): from Latin <span class=\"ei\">permittere</span>, from <span class=\"ei\">per-</span> ‘through’ + <span class=\"ei\">mittere</span> ‘send, let go’.</span></span></span></div></ol><span class=\"dictlink-g\"><span class=\"dictlink\">See <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/american_english/permit_1\" title=\" definition in American English\n \"><span class=\"xh\">permit</span></a> in the Oxford Advanced American Dictionary</span><span class=\"dictlink\">See <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/academic/permit1\" title=\" definition in Academic English\n \"><span class=\"xh\">permit</span></a> in the Oxford Learner's Dictionary of Academic Englis